It's very capital intensive. And Hermes and AJ. Have just taken a completely

02:38.532 --> 02:42.142
different approach, so it's definitely worth diving into. I want both companies

02:42.196 --> 02:45.426
to succeed genuinely, just because it'd be really cool to be able to fly from

02:45.448 --> 02:49.134
New York to London in 90 minutes. And It Would Also be Great if America

02:49.182 --> 02:52.946
Could solve the hypersonic vehicle problem and have that

02:52.968 --> 02:56.722
technology defending us. But I

02:56.776 --> 03:00.418
like how Hermes has kind of decomposed the problem on their side, as you'll

03:00.434 --> 03:04.082
see. So let's go into kind of why this matters.

03:04.146 --> 03:07.554
So the first thing is that the race for hypersonic weapons

03:07.602 --> 03:10.986
is super, super real right now. A lot of know it

03:11.008 --> 03:14.538
just gets lost in the headlines about Russia, China, Ukraine, Taiwan. There's all

03:14.544 --> 03:18.042
these different headlines going on, all these different geopolitical things.

03:18.176 --> 03:21.786
But hypersonic weapons are a really big deal, and I'll

03:21.818 --> 03:25.290
explain why. So we actually have hypersonic weapons.

03:25.450 --> 03:29.214
They're just rocket powered. So any ICBM is

03:29.252 --> 03:31.360
hypersonic. They travel at like, Mach 15,

03:32.050 --> 03:35.426
and every SpaceX rocket that goes into orbit goes

03:35.528 --> 03:39.042
well past hypersonic. And there isn't actually a true

03:39.096 --> 03:43.202
hypersonic barrier. There's a supersonic barrier, which is very much

03:43.256 --> 03:46.290
defined by physics. It's the point at which there's a sonic boom.

03:46.950 --> 03:50.742
And so it's very, very hard to get past that. But with hypersonics, that happens

03:50.796 --> 03:54.514
around mach five. But it isn't a very specific binary

03:54.562 --> 03:58.294
moment. It's just a moment where you're going so fast that the air chemistry around

03:58.332 --> 04:01.610
the vehicle changes. So there's a whole bunch of new problems

04:01.680 --> 04:05.046
that you need to solve as an aircraft designer. And it's something that's really held

04:05.078 --> 04:08.246
the technology back. It works very well on missiles,

04:08.438 --> 04:12.166
where you're sending off a rocket and you don't really care that it's

04:12.198 --> 04:15.454
going to come back because it's going to crash into your target. But in terms

04:15.492 --> 04:19.680
of reusable craft, which is obviously the future, hypersonic has been

04:20.210 --> 04:24.034
a real tough thing to solve. And the fear is

04:24.072 --> 04:28.158
that China is developing hypersonic

04:28.174 --> 04:31.678
missiles in Russia as well. And these hypersonic missiles can potentially carry

04:31.694 --> 04:35.298
a nuclear warhead or potentially take out an aircraft carrier. And that creates kind of

04:35.304 --> 04:38.806
a zone of defense around China that won't allow

04:38.988 --> 04:42.838
our aircraft carriers to maneuver into position. And if you

04:42.844 --> 04:46.082
remember, during the Taiwan strait cris, we actually brought

04:46.146 --> 04:49.810
two aircraft carrier groups into the Taiwan strait to kind of defend Taiwan.

04:49.890 --> 04:53.110
And if China has hypersonic missiles, we wouldn't be able to do that. And that's

04:53.610 --> 04:57.530
a big problem. And now the reason that hypersonic missiles and hypersonic weapons are so

04:57.600 --> 05:00.858
important is because it kind of splits the difference between what you get with an

05:00.864 --> 05:04.182
ICBM, which is really, really fast, but ultimately very predictable,

05:04.246 --> 05:07.594
because you're launching this rocket, it shoots off from the ground,

05:07.642 --> 05:11.018
and it's on a parabolic curve, and you can kind of intercept it very easily.

05:11.114 --> 05:14.482
On the flip side, you have a cruise missile which is

05:14.536 --> 05:18.706
targeted with a turbofan. It's basically like a fighter jet, and that

05:18.728 --> 05:22.382
means it's very maneuverable. If you've seen the old James Bond

05:22.446 --> 05:25.858
GoldenEye, I think it's GoldenEye. There's this moment where

05:25.864 --> 05:28.706
they fire off the cruise missile, and it's like flying through the canyons, and it's

05:28.728 --> 05:32.306
evading defenses. It's going very low and it's very unpredictable. So it's hard to shoot

05:32.338 --> 05:36.146
down, but it's ultimately slow so it can be shot down. And we have systems

05:36.178 --> 05:39.790
for that. But no one can shoot down a hypersonic missile

05:39.810 --> 05:43.398
at this point because it goes so fast, mach Five, and it's also maneuverable.

05:43.494 --> 05:47.590
So blending those two things together is really, really valuable.

05:47.670 --> 05:51.338
Now, Hermes isn't building hypersonic missiles. They're building hypersonic aircraft.

05:51.434 --> 05:54.894
And so that has a number of different applications. The first

05:54.932 --> 05:59.002
is ISR or intelligence surveillance and Reconnaissance,

05:59.146 --> 06:02.654
which is basically cameras and sensors on a plane. And this

06:02.692 --> 06:06.194
will allow the Hermes craft to kind of get

06:06.232 --> 06:09.550
into enemy airspace and take photos and do reconnaissance

06:09.630 --> 06:13.138
without getting shot down because it's traveling so fast. But it's also not

06:13.304 --> 06:16.766
predictable, the trajectory. And then ultimately,

06:16.798 --> 06:20.806
they do want to turn into a weapons platform and deploy drop bombs or

06:20.828 --> 06:23.926
drop missiles from it. And then ultimately, in the long,

06:23.948 --> 06:26.978
long term, they want to be able to carry people because obviously that would unlock

06:26.994 --> 06:30.738
a ton of really interesting applications. So the

06:30.764 --> 06:34.490
government has been working on this for a very long time. There's the SR 72,

06:34.560 --> 06:38.826
which is Lockheed's successor to the SR 71. That program,

06:39.008 --> 06:42.326
it was made public and then it was made private again when the stakes

06:42.358 --> 06:45.706
got raised and people started worrying about the hypersonic

06:45.738 --> 06:49.294
race really heating up. So we don't know that much about the SR 72

06:49.332 --> 06:52.794
project. But then there's also the Air Force's Mayhem

06:52.842 --> 06:56.174
project, which is another hypersonic program.

06:56.292 --> 07:00.142
And so Hermes is in kind of a very exciting

07:00.206 --> 07:03.714
space. But they're really the main startup that's really trying

07:03.752 --> 07:07.374
to go after this problem with kind of that startup mentality, really quick iteration.

07:07.422 --> 07:11.142
And we'll kind of get into their process of how they have

07:11.196 --> 07:14.710
solved some of the really hard problems to be able to iterate on this problem

07:14.780 --> 07:18.486
really quickly. And so the other

07:18.508 --> 07:22.060
point is that it's just an interesting company. They've raised $100 million from really cool

07:22.430 --> 07:26.058
investors. Kosla did their first round. Canaan did

07:26.064 --> 07:28.986
