16:53.190 --> 16:56.466
And so they get the money from

16:56.568 --> 17:00.306
Kosla and

17:00.328 --> 17:04.162
then they start building their first engine. So they basically built

17:04.216 --> 17:08.546
this, I saw as a very rudimentary turbojet

17:08.738 --> 17:12.454
that spins up and provides some propellant into

17:12.492 --> 17:16.118
the Ramjet and then at a certain point flips over and then you're using the

17:16.124 --> 17:19.266
Ramjet power. And that's kind of the whole model.

17:19.388 --> 17:23.094
They're now building what's called the Chimera engine because obviously Chimera

17:23.142 --> 17:26.890
is like two things melded together and that

17:26.960 --> 17:30.650
really unlocks their ability to go both take off from the ground and

17:30.720 --> 17:34.494
go slow, but then also go really, really fast once the Ramjet kicks on.

17:34.612 --> 17:38.126
And so they get through this, they go and they

17:38.148 --> 17:41.294
build the first engine. And then they have to go and test it.

17:41.332 --> 17:44.994
And there's only like one or two wind

17:45.032 --> 17:48.386
tunnels that can actually test hypersonic engines that

17:48.408 --> 17:51.938
are publicly available. Or you can just they have capacity. There are

17:51.944 --> 17:55.026
probably some private ones, but startups don't have access to

17:55.048 --> 17:59.750
those. And I actually talked to this defense journalist, Alex Hollings,

18:00.730 --> 18:04.566
and I asked him if there was one thing that you could do if

18:04.588 --> 18:08.482
you were the President for a day, what would you do to help

18:08.556 --> 18:12.454
America win the race for hypersonic weaponry?

18:12.582 --> 18:17.222
And I was expecting him to, you know, pump some money into grants,

18:17.366 --> 18:20.670
know, accelerate this project or that project. And he told me, no,

18:20.740 --> 18:24.206
the one thing that the government needs to do is have more

18:24.308 --> 18:27.482
hypersonic testing tunnels built at various

18:27.546 --> 18:31.514
academic institutions and research facilities because that's

18:31.562 --> 18:35.754
truly where the key bottleneck

18:35.802 --> 18:39.282
is right now, in hypersonic research. So the guys drive

18:39.336 --> 18:43.058
their engine up to Indiana. I think they went to Notre Dame, where they

18:43.064 --> 18:46.274
have the tunnel, and they test it and it works, and they get good data

18:46.312 --> 18:49.766
and they prove that this idea of running the

18:49.788 --> 18:54.066
turbojet engine and then switching over to the Ramjet at a certain speed,

18:54.178 --> 18:57.910
it will work. And so that unlocks their Series A and then

18:58.060 --> 19:00.390
they get that done with Canaan.

19:02.810 --> 19:06.650
It's really funny about Ramjets everyone I've talked to who's technical in

19:06.720 --> 19:09.986
the defense tech hard tech world just loves

19:10.038 --> 19:13.658
Ramjets. There's this famous story about Palmer Lucky,

19:13.754 --> 19:17.294
where when Trey Stevens was pitching him the idea for

19:17.332 --> 19:20.990
Anderol, Palmer was already building a Ramjet

19:21.490 --> 19:25.406
in his swimming pool in Woodside, I think, and the neighbors were

19:25.428 --> 19:28.482
getting called, the cops were getting called because he's like building this crazy thing.

19:28.536 --> 19:31.726
But clearly every tinkerer loves Ramjets.

19:31.838 --> 19:35.806
And it's really cool to see Hermes finally trying to figure out how to commercialize

19:35.838 --> 19:39.654
these in a really serious way because it's a very old technology. But the

19:39.692 --> 19:42.790
real problem is not necessarily the

19:42.860 --> 19:46.134
tech risk here. And that's always kind of the best

19:46.332 --> 19:49.786
thing in defense tech startups is

19:49.808 --> 19:53.894
when they're not science projects, they're not trying to go off and invent

19:53.942 --> 19:57.690
an entirely new material or do fundamental material science research or

19:57.760 --> 20:01.450
have some fundamental breakthrough. It's more like the technology works.

20:01.520 --> 20:04.078
We just need to put it together in a different way. And then we need

20:04.084 --> 20:07.486
to solve all the hard steps of fundraising and then

20:07.588 --> 20:11.134
actually selling this into the military because that's obviously a really hard part.

20:11.252 --> 20:15.150
And so getting

20:15.220 --> 20:18.306
into the military and actually solving the Valley of

20:18.328 --> 20:22.290
Death is a theme that I've seen with all these companies. And so

20:22.360 --> 20:25.842
the way Hermes solved it was, first off, they hired this great guy from

20:25.896 --> 20:29.078
Anderol who had worked there and had a bunch of experience selling to the

20:29.084 --> 20:31.750
military. And then they really,

20:31.820 --> 20:35.026
really take a broad approach to what they're willing

20:35.058 --> 20:39.010
to do with government contracts. So their first contract,

20:39.090 --> 20:43.226
I believe, was to evaluate the viability of

20:43.248 --> 20:46.826
a hypersonic Air Force One. And I

20:46.848 --> 20:48.906
think they had a couple of million bucks in the bank. There was no way

20:48.928 --> 20:53.214
that they were going to promise to build a hypersonic Air Force One. But the

20:53.252 --> 20:56.954
fact that they were still able to get a contract

20:57.002 --> 21:00.382
and actually get some response from the government

21:00.436 --> 21:04.334
and get some buy in that, hey, we will actually

21:04.372 --> 21:07.906
give you money. There's now revenue on the books just to deliver kind

21:07.928 --> 21:11.266
of just a report and some data. And that's been some of

21:11.288 --> 21:14.626
the early projects. Everyone, obviously you want

21:14.648 --> 21:17.846
to drive to program of record where the military and

21:17.868 --> 21:21.698
the government is buying a capability on an ongoing basis. They're actually deploying

21:21.714 --> 21:25.698
it. It's having an impact. But with something that's as complicated as building a hypersonic

21:25.794 --> 21:29.574
aircraft, it's just not going to happen in year one or year two or

21:29.612 --> 21:33.434
even year three. So getting to the point, really understanding that

21:33.472 --> 21:37.078
and getting revenue on the books by doing these small programs

21:37.094 --> 21:40.534
where they can just turn over data or reports or just build one

21:40.592 --> 21:44.414
small piece for the government, but still satisfy and get good

21:44.452 --> 21:48.110
reviews and then get ready for the next contract, that's been a really

21:48.180 --> 21:52.270
big piece. And so one interesting

21:52.420 --> 21:56.286
learning, I mean, there's a bunch of interesting learnings, but one thing that they focused

21:56.318 --> 22:00.494
on throughout my conversation and my tour of the facility

22:00.622 --> 22:03.902
was the machine that builds the machine.

22:04.046 --> 22:08.002
So they're not just focused on building one aircraft,

22:08.066 --> 22:11.826
they really need to solve the entire supply chain

22:11.938 --> 22:15.698
and figure out how they can build an organization

22:15.794 --> 22:19.910
that produces these aircraft at scale

22:19.990 --> 22:23.578
in numbers pretty quickly. Because if it works,

22:23.744 --> 22:27.562
we know that the demand is know, russia and China are building

22:27.616 --> 22:31.354
a lot of these hypersonic weapons already. And so as soon as this

22:31.392 --> 22:34.270
thing is ready to go, the government will need a lot of them. And so

22:34.340 --> 22:37.566
hermes is going to need to solve their supply chain issues. So I think

22:37.588 --> 22:40.794
they got an investment from raytheon. And raytheon owns pratt and Whitney,

22:40.842 --> 22:44.298
which makes jet engines for American fightercraft.

22:44.394 --> 22:47.954
I think the f 22, it might be the f 16, but they've actually

22:47.992 --> 22:51.246
bought two of these huge pratt and whitney turbojet

22:51.278 --> 22:55.074
engines. And then they're going to basically take off

22:55.112 --> 22:58.694
the back, the afterburner of those

22:58.892 --> 23:02.034
jet engines and then attach their ram jets

23:02.082 --> 23:05.638
to them. And that will be the way that they build their engine.

23:05.724 --> 23:09.094
And it's very interesting because they're clearly obsessed with this idea of

23:09.132 --> 23:12.166
build versus buy. There's a lot that they still have to build. They're constantly,

23:12.198 --> 23:15.306
I mean, for the first version, I was

23:15.328 --> 23:19.034
talking to the co founder about how

23:19.072 --> 23:22.714
they were bending the pipes themselves and welding everything together themselves.

23:22.832 --> 23:26.894
And now they have really big 3D printing machines and all sorts of different ways

23:26.932 --> 23:30.302
to fabricate parts. But something as complicated as a jet engine,

23:30.356 --> 23:33.794
they're not going to be able to rebuild that internally, at least

23:33.832 --> 23:37.294
not anytime soon. So that's kind of why they've partnered and how they're

23:37.342 --> 23:40.978
thinking about building the machine that builds the

23:40.984 --> 23:44.562
machine. It's a really interesting phrase. And then

23:44.696 --> 23:48.434
that obviously really puts them in a different strategy

23:48.482 --> 23:52.130
as boom, which was originally, I think, partnered with rolls Royce

23:52.210 --> 23:55.654
to buy their engine. But then that didn't work

23:55.692 --> 23:58.954
out. I'm not exactly sure why. But now boom is trying to build

23:58.992 --> 24:02.022
a fully custom engine and it's going to be incredibly capital intensive.

24:02.166 --> 24:06.042
And the way boom is solving it is they're going off and getting

24:06.096 --> 24:10.614
money from the airlines

24:10.662 --> 24:14.238
and basically saying, hey, if you want access to

24:14.404 --> 24:18.010
supersonic aircraft on your most important flight routes,

24:18.090 --> 24:21.374
you better pony up and give us $200 million up front, or something

24:21.412 --> 24:23.360
like that. I don't exactly know the numbers,

24:25.110 --> 24:28.562
but for hermes, the government wants them

24:28.616 --> 24:31.778
to really bring this to market as fast as possible. And obviously they don't want

24:31.784 --> 24:35.818
to get stuck in the integration hell technical quagmire

24:35.854 --> 24:39.926
that might come with trying to build a turbojet or

24:39.948 --> 24:43.874
turbofan engine by themselves, especially when the off the shelf

24:43.922 --> 24:47.742
stuff works. And then the last thing that I noticed

24:47.826 --> 24:51.610
with hermes that's kind of very interesting

24:51.680 --> 24:55.802
and maybe under discussed is that even though they're all

24:55.856 --> 24:59.798
engineers and they had all this trouble pitching

24:59.814 --> 25:03.534
the company in the early days, but they're all really good

25:03.572 --> 25:07.198
at media now and I think they really understand the value of media. Even in

25:07.204 --> 25:09.950
a hard tech business where you're not selling to consumers,

25:10.370 --> 25:13.934
their customers, ultimately it's the government, at least

25:13.972 --> 25:18.386
for the next who knows how many years. But they

25:18.408 --> 25:21.746
have a podcast and they do a lot of media and they let YouTubers come

25:21.768 --> 25:25.026
in and tour it and make videos and stuff and they

25:25.048 --> 25:28.982
talk publicly about what they're building and I think that that

25:29.036 --> 25:32.278
really lets them solve. They're in Atlanta, they're going to need to

25:32.284 --> 25:35.462
pull people from all over the place to build this

25:35.516 --> 25:38.860
really solid engineering team. And so

25:39.550 --> 25:42.906
by having all of the co founders talk about the company culture, talk about

25:42.928 --> 25:45.500
the company evangelize for what they're doing,

25:45.950 --> 25:50.286
they're able to bring the

25:50.308 --> 25:53.806
customer is almost the employee. So they're able to recruit a bunch of people and

25:53.828 --> 25:57.102
then they're also able to have

25:57.156 --> 26:00.974
a really polished resource for

26:01.172 --> 26:05.114
the various politicians to get up to speed in Silicon

26:05.162 --> 26:08.434
Valley. I feel like everyone knows androol but

26:08.472 --> 26:11.826
I was talking to a congressman a couple months ago who had

26:11.848 --> 26:15.614
no idea what Androl was it just wasn't on his radar

26:15.662 --> 26:19.246
and he was telling me that he has defense

26:19.278 --> 26:22.486
budget to allocate and obviously anderol has

26:22.508 --> 26:26.066
like I think they have a hundred person team in Washington DC.

26:26.178 --> 26:29.914
Just to help sell to the government, educate people. But there's just the government's so

26:29.952 --> 26:33.366
big, there's hundreds of elected officials

26:33.398 --> 26:36.826
and then, like, thousands of people in the DoD that you might

26:36.848 --> 26:40.282
need to coordinate with. And so being able to tell

26:40.336 --> 26:43.878
your story, the Hermias team being able to

26:43.904 --> 26:47.454
tell their story is really, really important to get

26:47.572 --> 26:50.846
the important people and the key decision makers up to speed, to be able to

26:50.868 --> 26:54.330
make a decision on a contract very, very quickly and maybe decide to

26:54.340 --> 26:58.386
take a meeting that they wouldn't otherwise. And I think that's kind of a

26:58.408 --> 27:01.762
new era and obviously Palmer's leading the charge there.

27:01.816 --> 27:06.180
But there are obviously things that certain

27:07.350 --> 27:09.878
defense tech companies aren't going to be able to talk about. Even while I was

27:09.884 --> 27:13.318
there, there were obviously things that were classified and they couldn't talk about.

27:13.404 --> 27:17.094
But there's still so much cool stuff that they can talk about know?

27:17.132 --> 27:20.330
It's not just like the culture of their company in Atlanta. It's also just like

27:20.400 --> 27:24.810
the history of this technology and why it's important the geopolitical implications,

27:25.390 --> 27:28.906
their fundraising story and what they're actually building. A lot of

27:28.928 --> 27:33.040
that isn't classified. Maybe the more minut details are,

27:33.810 --> 27:38.334
but I was just very surprised that they were

27:38.372 --> 27:41.726
so open and are so capable of

27:41.748 --> 27:45.534
telling their story and really articulating why

27:45.572 --> 27:48.974
this is such an important thing. So yeah,

27:49.012 --> 27:53.134
that's the story of Hermes. I'm going to do a bigger video on this and

27:53.172 --> 27:56.246
cut together a bunch of the interview footage that I got while I

27:56.268 --> 27:58.534
was there. And yeah, I'm excited to share that with.
